We learnt about the Basic Sync function

Sync function is executed one by one 




function getData() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        setTimeout(() => {
            resolve("Data received");
        }, 2000);
    });
}
getData().then((data) => {
    console.log(data);
}).catch((error) => {
    console.error("Error:", error);
});




>>>>Set Time out function
->> it will print the data one time after some milliseconds
whatever we have given

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Data received");
}, 5000);


>>>>>>>>>>>setInterval
->> It will print the data after regular intervals unless we stop it ourself


setInterval(() => {
    console.log("Checking for new data...");
}, 3000);



Now We worked on various API's key and perform various opertaion

API: A set of rules that allows software applications to communicate with each other.


Endpoint: A specific URL where an API can be accessed.


Request: A message sent by a client to an API to get or send data.

Response: The data returned by the API after processing a request.

HTTP Methods: Actions like GET (fetch), POST (create), PUT (update), DELETE (remove).


REST API: An API that follows REST architecture using HTTP methods.


JSON: A lightweight format used to exchange data in APIs.


Authentication: Verifying the identity of a user or application (e.g., API key, token).


Authorization: Granting permission to access specific resources.


API Key: A unique code used to identify and authenticate a user.


Rate Limiting: Restricting the number of API requests in a given time.


Status Codes: Numeric responses indicating success or error (e.g., 200, 404).


Headers: Extra information sent with requests or responses.


Payload: The actual data sent in a request or response.


SDK: A toolkit that helps developers use APIs easily.


Webhook: An API that sends real-time data automatically when an event occurs
 